==Old English==
===Etymology===
Representing the Indo-European demonstrative pronoun ''*siā, *sā'', adapted in West Germanic as the definite article by analogy with the ''t-'' stem forms (Old English [[þæt]]).  Cognate with Old Norse [[sú]], Gothic [[𐍃𐍉]], Greek [[ἡ]].  See also the masculine forms under [[se#Old English|se]].

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /se:o/

===Demonstrative Pronoun===
'''sēo''' ''f''
# definite article: [[the]]
#:''seo cwen'': the woman
# demonstrative adjective: [[that]], [[those]]
#:''þa giefe geaf Widsið'': Widsith gave that gift
# pronoun: [[she]], [[they]]
#:''þa ne sacað'': they do not quarrel

===Declension===
*Nominative: '''sēo''' (''plural'' '''þā''')
*Accusative: '''þā''' (''plural'' '''þā''')
*Genitive: '''þǣre''' (''plural'' '''þāra''', '''þǣra''')
*Dative: '''þǣre''' (''plural'' '''þǣm''', '''þām''')

===See also===
